node.text:
110 W Gaston St, Savannah, GA 31401
$2,950,000, 6 bd, 7 ba, 7,912 sqft

This magnificent freestanding Italianate Victorian home is perfectly positioned on Gaston Street in Savannah’s Landmark District, steps from Forsyth Park & Bull Street. Originally built for Confederate Capt. Nathan B. Brown in 1874 & featured in the movie “Savannah,” this grand home offers the ultimate in Savannah style, plus elevator access to all floors & 3-car attached garage. Discover stunning period details, bay windows, exceptional millwork, elegant parlors, inlaid parquet floors, arched doorways, 14-foot ceilings & 3 covered side porches. Surrounded by wrought iron fencing & ideal for entertaining, this lovely home boasts a grand parlor with bay windows, fireplace, pocket doors, crystal chandeliers & access to the covered side porch via original Italianate doors. A renovated chef’s kitchen has stainless steel appliances, granite countertops & an open design with a spacious sitting area, brick fireplace & English pub-style bar. Income-producing garden apartment, workshop & more.

Listed by:
Staci M Donegan
Seabolt Brokers LLC

node.text:
The Katharine Seymour Day House is a historic house at 77 Forest Street in the historic Nook Farm district of Hartford, Connecticut. Built in 1884 for a local businessman seeking to compete stylistically with the adjacent Mark Twain House, it is a good local example of Queen Anne architecture. It now serves as the administrative center and library for the Harriet Beecher Stowe Center. It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1971. Photo by @restoringyourhistorichouse

node.text:
132 Carlton St, Brookline, MA 02446
$4,680,000, 11 bd, 11 ba, 10,792 sqft

Opportunity for a visionary ! Sophistication, Beauty, and Charm! One-of-a-kind 1908 built mansion in Brookline’s Cottage Farm Historic District. Impressive French Beaux-Arts style designed by Boston architects Kilham & Hopkins. Mahogany millwork, high ceilings, dramatic curved staircase, and beautiful craftsmanship of the past century. French pocket doors, stately-proportioned rooms, oversized kitchen with pantry prep area, built-in window seats, and an elevator. Stucco & stone exterior. Garage parking and deeded parking space. Residence offers its new owners the opportunity to design and execute a renovation for a unique generational home. Fantastic location, convenient to Whole Foods, Tatte Bakery, Down Under Yoga Studio & other shops on Beacon at St. Mary’s. Proximity to Back Bay, Longwood Medical Area, Fenway Park, Coolidge Corner & BU. Property offered As is. Merits and deserves renovation. Roof has been replaced in December 2019.

Listed by:
Esin Susol
Castles Unlimited®

node.text:
John Augustus Reitz Home built in 1871 in Evansville, IN, now open as a museum for tours. It is one of Indiana’s most impressive Victorian home museums, with much of the interior and exterior original appointments in tact, including the family furniture. Photos by @barclayproductions and via @reitz_home_museum

The Henry W. Merriam House is located in Newton, Sussex County, New Jersey, United States. Owned by industrialist Henry Wilson Merriam (1828-1900), the owner of the Merriam Shoe Company, the house was built in 1883 and was added to the National Register of Historic Places on December 18, 1970. It is Newton's prime example of high Victorian architecture. Photo by Dave Mills

node.text:
The Elms is a large mansion located at 367 Bellevue Avenue, Newport, Rhode Island, completed in 1901. The architect Horace Trumbauer (1868–1938) designed it for the coal baron Edward Julius Berwind (1848–1936), taking inspiration from the 18th century Château d'Asnières in Asnières-sur-Seine, France. C. H. Miller and E. W. Bowditch, working closely with Trumbauer, designed the gardens and landscape. The Preservation Society of Newport County purchased The Elms in 1962, and opened the house to the public. The Elms was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1971, and designated a National Historic Landmark in 1996. Photo by @kevinmu
